    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become so deeply connected that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, no matter the distance between them. It's like having a pair of magical, talking shoes that always know what the other is doing, even if they're on opposite sides of the world. This connection is so strong that if you change the state of one shoe, the other shoe changes its state simultaneously, as if they were whispering secrets to each other through the fabric of the universe.\n\nNow, let's compare this to classical correlation. In the world of classical physics, things are more like two friends who share a secret handshake. If one friend knows the handshake, the other friend can learn it too, but they don't have any magical connection. They can only share information through slower, more conventional means, like sending a letter or a phone call. So, while classical correlation involves a relationship between objects, it's not as instant or as mysterious as quantum entanglement.\n\nIn summary, quantum entanglement is like having a pair of enchanted shoes that always know what the other is doing, while classical correlation is more like sharing a secret handshake between friends. Both involve some form of connection, but quantum entanglement",
